.\" SPDX-License-Identifier: GPL-2.0-only
.\" Man page for safexec, part of NPP (Nginx Cache Purge Preload) for WordPress
.TH SAFEXEC 1 "2025" "safexec 1.9.6" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
safexec \- secure privilege-dropping wrapper for controlled external command execution
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B safexec
.RI [ wrapper " " args ...]
.I program
.RI [ args ... ]
.br
.B safexec
.BI --kill= pid
.br
.B safexec
.RB { --help | -h }
.br
.B safexec
.RB { --version | -v }
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B safexec
executes a restricted, compile-time allowlisted set of external programs
(e.g.
.BR wget (1),
.BR curl (1))
from higher-level contexts such as PHP. It is the privilege-dropping
backend used by the NPP (Nginx Cache Purge Preload) WordPress plugin in
place of a raw
.B shell_exec()
call.
.PP
When installed setuid-root,
.B safexec
sanitizes its environment, resolves the requested tool (and any leading
wrapper commands) to absolute paths under trusted system directories,
drops privileges before exec, and applies best-effort resource isolation
(cgroup v2, or a POSIX rlimits fallback).
.PP
When the effective uid at runtime is not 0 (not installed setuid-root, or
setuid bit lost/ignored, e.g. on a
.B nosuid
mount), it runs in
.B pass-through mode
instead: the allowlist and absolute-path pinning are still enforced, but
environment sanitization, privilege dropping, resource isolation, and the
percent-encoding normalization shim (see
.B PCTNORM
below) are all skipped, and the target is exec'd immediately as the
original caller.
.SH ALLOWED PROGRAMS
Only the following compile-time allowlisted binaries may be executed
(anything else is refused with a diagnostic on stderr):
.TP
.B Scan
.BR rg (1)
.TP
.B Fetch
.BR wget (1),
.BR curl (1)
.TP
.B Archives
.BR tar (1),
.BR gzip (1),
.BR gunzip (1),
.BR xz (1),
.BR unxz (1),
.BR zip (1),
.BR unzip (1)
.TP
.B Checksums
.BR sha256sum (1),
.BR sha512sum (1),
.BR shasum (1),
.BR b2sum (1),
.BR cksum (1)
.TP
.B Media / images
.BR ffmpeg (1),
.BR ffprobe (1),
.BR magick (1),
.BR convert (1),
.BR identify (1)
.TP
.B Documents
.BR wkhtmltopdf (1),
.BR pdftk (1),
.BR pandoc (1)
.PP
The following buckets are compiled in only if the corresponding
preprocessor macro was defined at build time (see
.B OPTIONAL TOOL BUCKETS
below):
.BR gs ;
.BR pdfinfo ,
.BR pdftoppm ,
.BR pdftocairo ;
.BR mysqldump ,
.BR mysql ,
.BR mariadb-dump ,
.BR mariadb ,
.BR pg_dump ,
.BR pg_restore ,
.BR psql ,
.BR redis-cli ;
.BR rsync ,
.BR git .
.SH COMMAND PRELUDE
Before the target program, a limited prelude of tokens may appear. Each
token in
.IR argv [1.. N -1]
is scanned in order (up to the point where an allowed program name is
recognized, which becomes the target) and must be one of:
.TP
.B A wrapper command
One of
.BR nohup ,
.BR nice ,
.BR timeout ,
.BR stdbuf ,
.BR ionice ,
.BR taskset ,
.BR setsid ,
.BR chrt ,
.BR time .
If given as a bare name, it is later resolved and pinned to an absolute
path under a trusted directory, exactly like the target program. If given
as an explicit path (containing
.BR / ),
that path is validated immediately: it must lie under a trusted binary
directory, and if it is a symlink, its resolved target must also lie
under a trusted directory \(em otherwise the whole prelude is rejected.
.TP
.B An option-looking token
Any token beginning with
.B -
(or exactly
.BR -- )
is passed through unexamined (e.g.
.B -n
for
.BR nice ,
.B 30
for
.BR timeout ).
.TP
.B A signed integer
A bare token consisting only of digits (optionally prefixed with
.B +
or
.BR - )
is passed through, to support numeric arguments to wrapper commands
(e.g. the delay argument to
.BR timeout ).
.TP
.B A NAME=VALUE assignment
Permitted only for a fixed proxy-related allowlist:
.BR HTTP_PROXY ,
.BR HTTPS_PROXY ,
.BR ALL_PROXY ,
.BR NO_PROXY
(and their lowercase equivalents). Any other assignment is rejected,
including but not limited to
.BR PATH ,
.BR IFS ,
.BR LD_PRELOAD ,
.BR LD_AUDIT ,
.BR LD_LIBRARY_PATH ,
.BR LD_DEBUG ,
.BR LD_ASSUME_KERNEL ,
.BR LD_ORIGIN_PATH ,
.BR LD_BIND_NOW ,
any
.BI DYLD_ *
variable,
.BR PYTHONPATH ,
.BR PERL5OPT ,
.BR RUBYOPT ,
.BR GEM_HOME ,
.BR GEM_PATH ,
.BR GCONV_PATH ,
.BR LOCPATH ,
.BR TZDIR ,
and
.BR MALLOC_CONF .
Unrecognized assignments are rejected by default.
.PP
A shell interpreter
.RB ( sh ", " bash ", " dash ", " ash ", " zsh ", " ksh ", " fish )
appearing anywhere in the prelude is explicitly rejected (e.g.
.B "safexec sh -c ..."
or
.BR "safexec /bin/sh ..." ),
regardless of any later allowed tool name in the argument list. Any other
unrecognized token ends the prelude scan at that point; if the token is
not itself an allowed program name, execution is refused.
.SH SECURITY MODEL
.TP
.B Absolute-path pinning
The target program (and any bare-name wrapper commands preceding it) is
resolved to an absolute path under a trusted directory \(em
.IR /usr/bin ", " /bin ", " /usr/local/bin ", " /usr/sbin ", " /sbin ,
.IR /usr/local/sbin ", " /run/current-system/sw/bin ", " /usr/pkg/bin ,
.I /usr/pkg/sbin
(NetBSD pkgsrc), and on macOS also
.IR /opt/homebrew/bin ", " /opt/homebrew/sbin ", " /opt/local/bin ,
.I /opt/local/sbin
\(em before exec. Regular files are accepted directly. Symlinks are
followed only when the resolved target still lives under a trusted
directory (this covers Alpine/BusyBox multi-call binaries such as
.B nohup
symlinked to
.BR coreutils );
the symlink path itself, not the resolved path, is what gets exec'd, so
the kernel sets
.B argv[0]
correctly for multi-call binaries. If no trusted candidate is found,
execution is refused.
.TP
.B Never exec as root
The target is never exec'd as root. Privileges are dropped to the
.B nobody
user before exec (except for
.BR rg ,
see
.B "RG-SPECIFIC BEHAVIOR"
below); if the drop fails, safexec falls back to the original caller's
uid/gid (e.g. the PHP-FPM worker's). If the effective uid is still 0 at
any point before exec, safexec aborts rather than proceed.
.TP
.B Environment sanitization
The environment is fully cleared early, then a minimal
.BR PATH ,
.BR LANG / LC_CTYPE / CHARSET
are set. The process umask is forced to
.B 077
and core dumps are disabled via
.BR PR_SET_DUMPABLE (0)
(Linux). Immediately before exec,
.B PR_SET_NO_NEW_PRIVS
is set to prevent the child from regaining privileges.
.TP
.B File descriptor hygiene
All inherited file descriptors numbered 3 and above are closed before
exec (via a single
.B close_range()
syscall on Linux 5.9+, falling back to scanning
.I /proc/self/fd
otherwise), except for any file descriptor
.B safexec
itself opened and validated for the exec (the
.B rg
cache directory fd, or the pctnorm shared-object fd), which must survive
into the child.
.TP
.B Resource isolation (Linux)
The process is moved into its own cgroup v2 child, named
.BI nppp. pid ,
always created under
.IR /sys/fs/cgroup/nppp ,
regardless of the session/service cgroup subtree the caller started in.
Relevant controllers
.RI ( memory ", " pids ", " cpu ", " io ", " cpuset )
are enabled on that parent where possible, and
.B cpuset.cpus
/
.B cpuset.mems
are propagated from parent to child when the child does not already set
them. Threaded cgroup subtrees are handled by moving the calling thread
into
.I cgroup.threads
and marking the child cgroup
.B threaded
when required. If cgroup v2 is unavailable, isolation falls back to
POSIX rlimits (with optional nice/ionice adjustments, unused by default).
.SH RG-SPECIFIC BEHAVIOR
Unlike every other allowed program,
.B rg
(ripgrep) does not drop privileges to
.BR nobody .
Instead:
.IP \(bu 3
The last command-line argument is assumed to be an absolute path to the
Nginx cache directory being scanned. It is opened directly with
.B O_DIRECTORY|O_NOFOLLOW
and validated via the resulting file descriptor (not by path, avoiding a
check/use race). A directory owned by
.B root
is always refused.
.IP \(bu 3
The path argument passed to
.B rg
is rewritten to
.BI /proc/self/fd/ n ,
referring to the exact, already-validated directory file descriptor, so
the directory
.B rg
actually scans cannot be swapped out between the validation check and
exec.
.IP \(bu 3
If the cache directory's owner uid matches the original caller's real
uid,
.B safexec
skips the privilege drop entirely and continues as the original caller.
.IP \(bu 3
Otherwise, safexec drops to the uid that owns the cache directory (which
must resolve to a valid
.I passwd
entry), not to
.BR nobody .
If that uid cannot be resolved, execution is refused.
.SH KILL MODE
.BI --kill= pid
terminates a process previously started by
.BR safexec .
The request succeeds only if both conditions hold:
.IP \(bu 3
The target process's real uid, read from
.IR /proc/ pid /status ,
matches the resolved uid of
.BR nobody .
.IP \(bu 3
The target process belongs to an
.BI nppp. *
safexec cgroup, per
.IR /proc/ pid /cgroup .
.PP
If the cgroup check fails (for example, in a container without cgroup
delegation),
.B safexec
falls back to checking the target's
.B NoNewPrivs
flag in
.IR /proc/ pid /status :
if it is set, the kill proceeds anyway (since
.B safexec
itself sets this flag on every child it starts); if not set, the kill is
refused.
.PP
Where the kernel supports it,
.BR pidfd_open (2)
/
.BR pidfd_send_signal (2)
are used to avoid PID-reuse race conditions; otherwise plain
.BR kill (2)
with
.B SIGTERM
is used as a fallback. This mode is Linux-only.
.SH PERCENT-ENCODING NORMALIZATION (PCTNORM)
When enabled
.RI ( "and only in privileged mode \(em never in pass-through mode" ),
.B safexec
can normalize percent-encoded characters in URLs passed to
.B wget
or
.B curl
by preloading a shared object via
.BR LD_PRELOAD .
Controlled by:
.TP
.B SAFEXEC_PCTNORM=1|0
Enable or disable the shim. Default: enabled
.RB ( 1 ).
.TP
.B SAFEXEC_PCTNORM_SO=/path/to/libnpp_norm.so
Path to the shim shared object. Default:
.IR /usr/lib/npp/libnpp_norm.so .
.TP
.B SAFEXEC_PCTNORM_CASE=upper|lower|off
Case normalization mode. Default:
.BR upper .
.PP
The shared object is only ever injected for
.B wget
or
.B curl
invocations, and only after validation: it must resolve (via
.BR realpath (3))
to a regular file located beneath a trusted library root
.RI ( /usr/lib ", " /lib ", " /usr/lib64 ", " /lib64 ),
owned by
.IR root:root ,
not group- or other-writable, and named exactly
.IR libnpp_norm.so .
The file is opened and validated once; on success,
.B LD_PRELOAD
is set to a
.I /proc/self/fd
reference to that already-open, already-checked descriptor \(em not the
original path string \(em so the object cannot be swapped out between
validation and the dynamic linker's own lookup at exec time. If
validation fails for any reason, the shim is silently skipped (a
diagnostic is still printed to stderr) and the environment remains
minimal.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.BI SAFEXEC_DETACH= mode
Selects the isolation strategy.
.I mode
is one of:
.RS
.TP
.B auto
(default) Prefer cgroup v2; fall back to rlimits if unavailable.
.TP
.B cgv2
Require cgroup v2; fail if it cannot be established.
.TP
.B rlimits
Skip cgroups; apply rlimits (and optional nice/ionice) only.
.TP
.B off
Apply no isolation tweaks at all.
.RE
.IP
Read via
.BR secure_getenv (3)
on glibc builds, or plain
.BR getenv (3)
on musl (which does not provide
.BR secure_getenv ).
.TP
.B SAFEXEC_QUIET=0|1
Suppress informational messages. Default:
.BR 0 .
.TP
.BI SAFEXEC_SAFE_CWD= mode
.BR -1 ,
.BR 0 ,
or
.BR 1 .
If
.BR 1 ,
.B safexec
changes to
.I /tmp
(or
.I /
as a last resort) when the current working directory is inaccessible. If
.B -1
(default), this is enabled only for interactive sessions (any of
stdin/stdout/stderr attached to a TTY).
.TP
.B SAFEXEC_PCTNORM, SAFEXEC_PCTNORM_SO, SAFEXEC_PCTNORM_CASE
See
.B "PERCENT-ENCODING NORMALIZATION (PCTNORM)"
above.
.SH BEHAVIOR NOTES
.IP \(bu 3
A fresh per-run cgroup name
.RI ( nppp. pid )
is used on every invocation. Empty, stale
.BI nppp. *
cgroups (in both the session/service subtree and the global
.I /sys/fs/cgroup/nppp
parent) are cleaned up automatically at the start of each run.
.IP \(bu 3
Locale selection is attempted in order:
.BR C.UTF-8 ,
then
.BR en_US.UTF-8 ,
then
.BR C .
.B CHARSET
is also set to aid BusyBox
.BR wget .
.IP \(bu 3
If
.I /tmp
is not writable by the final effective uid and the command being run is
.B wget
with exactly
.B "-P /tmp"
as adjacent arguments,
.B safexec
rewrites the destination to
.IR /tmp/nppp-cache/ euid ,
provided the parent directory
.I /tmp/nppp-cache
is root-owned, mode
.BR 01777 ,
and not a symlink (safexec ensures this directory exists on every
privileged run). Otherwise the original
.B "-P /tmp"
argument is left untouched and a warning is printed.
.IP \(bu 3
On platforms lacking
.BR O_NOFOLLOW ,
open-time symlink protection is compiled out (reduced at build time).
.SH PORTABILITY
On Linux,
.B safexec
supports cgroup v2 joining, pidfd-based process termination where the
kernel provides it, I/O priority adjustment, POSIX rlimits, single-syscall
file-descriptor closing via
.BR close_range (2)
(with a
.I /proc/self/fd
scan fallback),
.BR PR_SET_NO_NEW_PRIVS ,
and
.BR PR_SET_DUMPABLE (0).
.PP
On BSD, macOS, and other POSIX systems, only rlimits and file-descriptor
closing are applied; cgroup and pidfd support are Linux-only, and
.B --kill
is refused outright on non-Linux systems.
.SH OPTIONAL TOOL BUCKETS (BUILD-TIME)
Additional allowlisted tools may be compiled in via preprocessor defines,
combined as needed:
.TP
.B -DSAFEXEC_WITH_GS
Adds
.BR gs (1)
(Ghostscript) for PostScript/PDF rasterization. Off by default:
Ghostscript has a long history of sandbox-escape and RCE CVEs via
crafted PS/PDF input. Enable only if PS/PDF rasterization is specifically
required and this exposure is understood.
.TP
.B -DSAFEXEC_WITH_POPPLER
Adds
.BR pdfinfo (1),
.BR pdftoppm (1),
.BR pdftocairo (1).
.TP
.B -DSAFEXEC_WITH_DB
Adds database client/dump tools:
.BR mysqldump ,
.BR mysql ,
.BR mariadb-dump ,
.BR mariadb ,
.BR pg_dump ,
.BR pg_restore ,
.BR psql ,
.BR redis-cli .
Enable only where intended.
.TP
.B -DSAFEXEC_WITH_RSYNC_GIT
Adds
.BR rsync (1)
and
.BR git (1).
Both can indirectly invoke
.BR ssh (1)
(via
.B "rsync -e"
or
.B git+ssh://
remotes), which escapes the allowlist's assumption of a closed set of
non-networked, no-shell-out tools. Enable only if you control how these
binaries are invoked.
.SH INSTALLATION
It is recommended to install
.B safexec
setuid-root:
.PP
.RS
.nf
chown root:root safexec
chmod 4755 safexec
.fi
.RE
.PP
Ensure the install location is not on a
.B nosuid
-mounted filesystem, or the setuid bit will be ignored by the kernel and
.B safexec
will silently run in pass-through mode on every invocation.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success: the target program was exec'd, or
.BR --help / --version
was requested, or
.B --kill
succeeded.
.TP
.B 1
Usage error, disallowed program, prelude validation failure, privilege-drop
failure, or exec failure.
.SH LIMITATIONS
.B safexec
is not a general-purpose sandbox. It constrains only the process it
execs and that process's descendants; it does not provide syscall-level
filtering. Only allowlisted tools may be run through the prelude rules
described above \(em arbitrary commands or shell pipelines are rejected.
.SH EXAMPLES
Fetch a URL with resource isolation applied automatically when installed
setuid-root:
.PP
.RS
.nf
safexec wget -q -O /tmp/nppp-cache/out.html https://example.com/
.fi
.RE
.PP
Run with a wrapper command and a numeric argument in the prelude:
.PP
.RS
.nf
safexec timeout 30 wget -q -O /tmp/out.html https://example.com/
.fi
.RE
.PP
Terminate a previously started safexec child by PID:
.PP
.RS
.nf
safexec --kill=12345
.fi
.RE
